      college town
      
      Davis is the ultimate college town. Itas green, laid back and friendly. You can walk or bike from the main campus to the main street in a few blocks. College students fill up the tables at nearby restaurants and coffee shops with their laptops, homework and friends. The town of Davis helps our students thrive.

      California
      
      UC Davis was founded in 1908 to serve the state of California. We do and we always will. And today, the seed that was planted those years ago has grown into one of the worldas top universities.

      academics
       UC Davis is a tier-one research university. Discoveries made by our students and faculty continue to improve the lives of people here in California and around the world. Explore our research In addition to our undergraduate and graduate study opportunities, we have professional schools in medicine, law, business, veterinary medicine, nursing and education.See our professional schools Through the Global Learning Hub, students can find global learning opportunities available on campus, in the region, and across all seven continents.Find opportunities Bodega Marine Laboratory (BML) is a leader in multidisciplinary research aimed at solving complex environmental problems in coastal ecosystems.Learn about the lab TERC is internationally recognized for its multidisciplinary, collaborative research on lakes and their surrounding watersheds.Explore TERC UC Davis Graduate Studies supports and advances graduate faculty-student mentoring through a variety of efforts, such as the Distinguished Graduate and Distinguished Postdoctoral Scholar Mentoring Awards.Meet our mentors
      We should take a moment to acknowledge the land on which UC Davis is located. For thousands of years, this land has been the home of Patwin people. Today, there are three federally recognized Patwin tribes: Cachil DeHe Band of Wintun Indians of the Colusa Indian Community, Kletsel Dehe Wintun Nation, and Yocha Dehe Wintun Nation. The Patwin people have remained committed to the stewardship of this land over many centuries. It has been cherished and protected, as elders have instructed the young through generations. We are honored and grateful to be here today on their traditional lands.
    UC Davis historyWe first opened our doors in 1908 as the University Farm, the research and science-based instruction extension of UC Berkeley. As the century evolved, our mission expanded beyond agriculture to match a larger understanding of how we should be serving the public.1909: After University Farm School opens in January with 18 students, more than 2,200 people attend the first Picnic Day in May.1916: Animals from the University Farm herd sweep championships at the Chicago International Livestock Show.1938: The campus is renamed the College of Agriculture at Davis. One hundred and six courses are taught by 76 faculty.1940: The Division of Chemistry acquires the first patents for the entire University of California.1959: The regents designate UC Davis and UC Riverside general campuses.1969: Begun as an aart happeninga, the Whole Earth Festival attracts 30,000 folks for eclectic music, henna tattoos, vegan food and regional crafts.1975: The veterinary school is ranked first in the nation by a national survey of deans.1990: The football team wins its 20th consecutive league championship, a national record.2018: UC Davis scientists unveil images from the worldas first total body scanner.Connecting our research and expertise to the effort to feed a growing population under a changing climate.Image UC Davis is applying its collective strengths in science, engineering, art and design to the problem of climate change and a warming planet. b'MenuOpen Search+ AdministrationGary S. May became UC Davisa seventh chancellor on Aug. 1, 2017. He oversees all aspects of the universityas teaching, research and public service mission.Chancellor May is boldly leading the university to new heights in academic excellence, enterprise research, public service and upward mobility for students from all backgrounds. He spearheaded the creation of aTo Boldly Go,a a 10-year  for the university and created  to ensure weare meeting studentsa basic needs. These include affordable housing, food security and mental health services.A strong proponent of innovation and economic development, one of Chancellor Mayas first significant efforts was partnering with the City of Sacramento to develop Aggie Square. This 25-acre ainnovation ecosystema on our UC Davis Health campus will be home to key research and academic programs and will serve as an incubator for start-ups.An electrical engineer, computer science expert and proud UC alumnus (UC Berkeley a88 and a91), Chancellor May is a dynamic leader with a passion for helping others succeed. He believes success is best judged by how we enhance the lives of others.Throughout his career, he has championed diversity and mentorship in both higher education and the workplace. He developed nationally recognized programs to attract, mentor and retain underrepresented groups in the STEM fields of science, technology, engineering and math.InitiativesPrinciples and policiesTop administrative unitsOrg chartStaff resources Begin Mailchimp Signup Form * indicates required***  real people should not fill this in and expect good things - do not remove this or risk form bot signupsEnd mc_embed_signupA Mary S. Croughan is a seasoned administrator in higher education with 30 years of experience with the University of California and three years at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas.As UC Davisa chief academic officer, her responsibilities include partnering with deans and faculty to achieve excellence across our academic mission of education, research and service. This includes implementing the strategic plan, strengthening and supporting the research enterprise, advancing student achievement and success, and fostering collaboration across UC Davis and in our communities. She oversees the university budget and daily campus operations, and partner with Chancellor May to develop Aggie Square.aIam thrilled that Mary will join my leadership team during such a pivotal time for higher education,a May said. aShe has deep roots in academia, and particularly with the UC system as an administrator and as a researcher in public health. She knows the impact and value of UC Davis, and we are proud to welcome her home.aWithin the University of California system, Croughan served as executive director of the Research Grants Program Office at the UC Office of the President from 2010 to 2017. There she oversaw seven grant programs to develop and implement UCas intramural research strategic vision, as well as overseeing research funds for the state of California.From 1987 to 2010, Croughan served as a faculty member at UC San Francisco in the School of Medicine. During her time with UCSF, she co-directed a required course in epidemiology and biostatistics and won multiple teaching awards, including the Academic Senateas Distinguished Teaching Award.Also at UCSF, Croughan developed and led a practice-based research network with more than 600 community-based primary care physicians. Since 1987, she has conducted research in reproductive and perinatal epidemiology, specifically examining health outcomes of nearly 52,000 women treated for infertility, and their partners and their children.Croughan served as vice chair and chair of the UC systemwide Academic Senate and as a faculty representative on the UC Board of Regents from 2007 to 2009. Throughout her career, she has served on numerous committees, including the UCSF Academic Senateas Committee on Academic Personnel, as chair of the Universitywide Committee on Academic Personnel and as chair of the UCSF Chancelloras Advisory Committee on the Status of Women.Croughan served as a fellow of the American Council on Education with University of Miami President Donna Shalala in 2012-13. As an ACE fellow, she studied higher education within the United States and internationally, enhancing her expertise in undergraduate education, fundraising, athletics and crisis communications.Vice Chancellor Pablo ReguerAnPrimary Image, One Shields Avenue, Davis, CA 95616 | 530-752-1011Copyright A The Regents of the University of California, Davis campus.       striving for equity
      
      The way we see it, the world is just too big to be bound by narrow perspectives. In an intellectually vibrant place like UC Davis, creativity connects ideas from the obvious to the outlandish. The most comprehensive solutions come from the most diverse minds. 
    Image 
      our students
      
      Building a culture of inclusion and opportunity takes real effort. The leaders and volunteers of our many student organizations work year-round to help undergraduates find their footing, their voice and each other. 

Below, youall read about people who overcame obstacles and led the way for others. Maybe you read that and think to yourself, aI couldnat do that.a But nobody reaches such levels of achievement alone. Aggies are competitive, but we also want each other to succeed. Whether you receive help, offer help or both, youave got a great big role to play here at UC Davis.
     Nouh Tekle found his home through our African Diaspora Policy Center and Black Student Union as well as his passion in social sciences.Read more Akshita Gandra is founder/editor of student social change zine The REVIVAL and was named a aForbes Under 30 Scholara in 2019.Read more Our First Generation Initiative connected Maribel Anguiano to her research, giving her the opportunity to join a lab and pursue STEM learning.Read moreThrough collaborative efforts with Student Affairs, Academic AffairsA and other community partners, the API Retention Initiative is dedicated to the academic, personalA and professional success of all UC Davis students who identify with the Asian Pacific Islander community.The Center for African Diaspora Student Success systemizes institutional collaborations and academic partnerships to create an approach tailored toward African diaspora student retention, persistenceA and graduation.The Center for Chicanx and Latinx Academic Student Success provides scholastic, socialA and personal support in a welcoming space where students can learn academic strategies, discover leadership and career development opportunities and explore employment prospects.The purpose of the LGBTQIA Resource Center is to provide an open, safe, inclusive space and community that promotes education and self-exploration for all sexes, genders and sexualities and their intersections with other identities. All are welcomed and celebrated.The NAASSC promotes a sense of belonging for Native American students and connects them with resources to enhance academic success. b"MenuOpen Search+ Locations
      locations
      
      Our main campus borders the Northern California city of Davis. Weare also located in Sacramento, the state capital, where UC Davis Health is headquartered.

The Davis campus is walkable from the city of Davis, a vibrant college town of about 68,000 people. The state capital is 20 minutes away, and world-class destinations such as the San Francisco Bay Area, Lake Tahoe and the Napa Valley are within a two-hour drive.

As the region's only academic health center, UC Davis Health is in Californiaas capital city of Sacramento.

      is within reach
      
      Weare a day trip away from the beach, snowy mountains, San Francisco, Silicon Valley and six national parks! The capital of California, Sacramento, is only 15 miles from Davis. Whether youare into skiing, museums, food, wine, technology, politics, big cities or wide open spaces, your interests are close to UC Davis.
    ImagetripsYou can unwind from school with easy getaways. You donat even need a car. Our campus is near Amtrak, which can take you to the Bay Area. Campus Recreation offers classes in white water rafting, rock climbing, snowshoeing and skiing that include transportation and equipment.       Californiaas capital has a lot more to offer than politics. Sacramento has a bikeable downtown with farm-to-fork restaurants, vintage shopping, NBA basketball games, award-winning coffee shops, live music, art museums, fairs, festivals, and more.

b'MenuOpen Search+ Wine country day trips
      wine country
      
      UC Davis is one of the world authorities in winemaking, and we helped to establish wine country in Northern California. We are surrounded by some of the best vineyards on earth. In under an hour, you can drive to Napa Valley, Mendocino County or the Sierra Nevada foothills.
    The world renowned Napa Valley is only a forty-five minute drive from campus.Image West of Napa, Sonoma County produces more wine than any other area in the state.Image In unspoiled coastal country, Mendocino offers a uniquely laidback wine country with amazing food.Image A quick drive southeast of Davis takes you to the charming wine country of the Sierra Nevada foothills.Image A quick drive south of Davis takes you to the emerging wine region of Lodi.Image The crowds are smaller, and the scenery and the wine quality matches some of the worldas top wineries.Image , One Shields Avenue, Davis, CA 95616 | 530-752-1011Copyright A The Regents of the University of California, Davis campus. b'MenuOpen Search+TransportationImagine almost 38,000-plus students, faculty, staff and visitors at UC Davis on the main Davis campus on any given weekday a and 85 percent of them travel here from off-campus. Whatas their transport of choice?On an average weekday, hereas how people get to UC Davis:We know the answer! Bikes, feet, skates, cars, buses, trainsA  a and the very occasional airplane. More than a third of those UC Davis commuters pedal to campus.Once cyclists enter the , our bike paths make it fast and efficient to get from class to laboratory to a workout at the .Newcomers can learn aboutA A on theA A websiteA so they will know the rules of the road. Safe cycling is one of many  our bicycling community.The campusas preference for two wheels has helped the city of Davis earn its aBicycle Capital of the U.S.a claim.
